PROJECT - GERMAN BANK LOAN

Objectives

The Objective of this project is for understanding and analyze the dataset which  contains the records of custormers who have taken loan from a German Bank and to  build an ML model to predict whether the customer will default or not based on th   historical information in the dataset.

def style_specific_cell(x):
    color_thresh = 'background-color: red'
    
    df_color = pd.DataFrame('', index=x.index, columns=x.columns)
    
    try:
        percentages = x.loc[x.iloc[:, 0] == "Percentage"].apply(lambda col: pd.to_numeric(col, errors='coerce'))
        df_color.loc[percentages < 10] = color_thresh
    except:
        pass
    
    return df_color

def style_stats_specific_cell(x):
    color_thresh = 'background-color: red'
    
    df_color = pd.DataFrame('', index=x.index, columns=x.columns)
    
    try:
        val_column = x.iloc[:, 1].apply(lambda val: float(val) if pd.notnull(val) else pd.NaT)
        df_color.iloc[val_column > 0.05, 1] = color_thresh
    except:
        pass
    
    return df_color


columns_cat = {name: df[name].nunique() for name in df.columns if df[name].dtype == 'O'}


marginal_report = {}

for itr in range(0,np.asarray(list(columns_cat.values())).max()+1):
    if [k for k,v in columns_cat.items() if v == itr]:
        marginal_report[itr]=[k for k,v in columns_cat.items() if v == itr]
        
for key in marginal_report.keys():
    marginal_percentage_report = pd.DataFrame()

    for name in sorted(marginal_report[key]):
        data = pd.crosstab(df[name], columns=["Percentage"]).apply(lambda r: round((r / r.sum()) * 100, 2), axis=0).reset_index()
        data.columns = [name, "Percentage"]
        data = data.transpose().reset_index()
        marginal_percentage_report = pd.concat([marginal_percentage_report, data], ignore_index=True)

    options = ["Category Option " + str(itr) for itr in range(1, marginal_percentage_report.shape[1])]
    marginal_percentage_report.columns = ["Attribute"] + options
    display(marginal_percentage_report.style.apply(style_specific_cell, axis=None))

def visualize_distribution(attributes):
    for attr in attributes:
        if attr not in df.columns:
            print(f"Error: {attr} not found in DataFrame.")
            continue

        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
        sns.set(style="whitegrid")

        # Create a countplot for the specified attribute
        sns.countplot(data=df, x=attr, hue='default', palette={"no": "blue", "yes": "red"})
        plt.title(f'Distribution of {attr} with respect to Default')

        # Improve readability by rotating x-axis labels
        plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')

        # Show counts on top of each bar
        ax = plt.gca()
        for p in ax.patches:
            ax.annotate(f'{p.get_height()}', (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                        ha='center', va='center', xytext=(0, 10), textcoords='offset points')

        plt.show()

age_interval = [18, 24, 35, 55, 120]

attributes_to_visualize = ['checking_balance', 'credit_history', 'purpose', 'savings_balance',

Encoding the data

In[10]:
le = LabelEncoder()

df["phone"] = le.fit_transform(df["phone"]).astype('int64')
df["default"] = le.fit_transform(df["default"]).astype('int64')

# Assuming df is your original DataFrame
cat_col_names = ["checking_balance", "credit_history", "purpose", "savings_balance", "employment_duration",
                 "other_credit", "housing", "job"]

# Initialize OneHotEncoder
encoder = OneHotEncoder(drop='first', sparse=False)

for attr in cat_col_names:
    # Reshape the column to a 2D array before fitting
    data = df[attr].values.reshape(-1, 1)
    
    # Fit and transform the data, and convert to a DataFrame
    encoded_data = pd.DataFrame(encoder.fit_transform(data), columns=encoder.get_feature_names_out([attr]))
    
    # Drop the original categorical column
    df.drop(attr, axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # Concatenate the one-hot encoded columns to the original DataFrame
    df = pd.concat([df, encoded_data], axis=1)

Splitting the data

In[12]:
X = df.drop(['default','age_Category'], axis=1)
y = df['default']

X = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)


pca = PCA(n_components=16)

X = pca.fit_transform(X)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

Cross-Validation

In[13]:
kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

# SVM
svm_model = SVC(kernel='rbf', random_state=1)
svm_scores = cross_val_score(svm_model, X_train, y_train, cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')
print(f'SVM Cross-Validation Accuracy: {svm_scores.mean():.3f}')

# Random Forest
rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1)
rf_scores = cross_val_score(rf_model, X_train, y_train, cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')
print(f'Random Forest Cross-Validation Accuracy: {rf_scores.mean():.3f}')

# XGBoost
xgb_model = XGBClassifier(random_state=1)
xgb_scores = cross_val_score(xgb_model, X_train, y_train, cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')
print(f'XGBoost Cross-Validation Accuracy: {xgb_scores.mean():.3f}')

# Decision Tree
dt_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)
dt_scores = cross_val_score(dt_model, X_train, y_train, cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')
print(f'Decision Tree Cross-Validation Accuracy: {dt_scores.mean():.3f}')

# Logistic Regression
lr_model = LogisticRegression(random_state=1)
lr_scores = cross_val_score(lr_model, X_train, y_train, cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')
print(f'Logistic Regression Cross-Validation Accuracy: {lr_scores.mean():.3f}')

Training and Testing different models

In[15]:
sc = StandardScaler()
X_train_std = sc.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_std = sc.transform(X_test)


svm_model = SVC(kernel='rbf', random_state=1, probability=True)
xgb_model = XGBClassifier()
rf_model = RandomForestClassifier()
lr_model = LogisticRegression(random_state=1)

svm_model.fit(X_train_std, y_train)
xgb_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
rf_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
lr_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

svm_preds = svm_model.predict(X_test_std)
xgb_preds = xgb_model.predict(X_test)
rf_preds = rf_model.predict(X_test)
lr_preds = lr_model.predict(X_test)

svm_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, svm_model.predict_proba(X_test_std)[:, 1])
xgb_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, xgb_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1])
rf_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, rf_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1])
lr_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, lr_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1])


results_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Model': ['SVM', 'XGBoost', 'Random Forest', 'Logistic Regression'],
    'Accuracy': [accuracy_score(y_test, svm_preds), accuracy_score(y_test, xgb_preds),
                 accuracy_score(y_test, rf_preds), accuracy_score(y_test, lr_preds)],
    'AUC': [svm_auc, xgb_auc, rf_auc, lr_auc]
})
In[16]:
# Get predicted probabilities for each model
svm_probs = svm_model.predict_proba(X_test_std)[:, 1]
xgb_probs = xgb_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
rf_probs = rf_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
lr_probs = lr_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Create ROC curves
fpr_svm, tpr_svm, _ = roc_curve(y_test, svm_probs)
fpr_xgb, tpr_xgb, _ = roc_curve(y_test, xgb_probs)
fpr_rf, tpr_rf, _ = roc_curve(y_test, rf_probs)
fpr_lr, tpr_lr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, lr_probs)

# Plot ROC curves
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', label='Random')
plt.plot(fpr_svm, tpr_svm, label=f'SVM (AUC = {roc_auc_score(y_test, svm_probs):.2f})')
plt.plot(fpr_xgb, tpr_xgb, label=f'XGBoost (AUC = {roc_auc_score(y_test, xgb_probs):.2f})')
plt.plot(fpr_rf, tpr_rf, label=f'Random Forest (AUC = {roc_auc_score(y_test, rf_probs):.2f})')
plt.plot(fpr_lr, tpr_lr, label=f'Logistic Regression (AUC = {roc_auc_score(y_test, lr_probs):.2f})')

plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('ROC Curves for Different Classifiers')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

print(results_df)
